      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "Could you comment on those Event here too? What does it do?\r\nBut make them short and easy to understand.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Added a one-line comment above each event: what it fires on and what its payload carries.",
      "line": 15
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "Rename this to GameSpeedMultiPlier.\r\n\r\nIs that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Renamed `SpeedMultiplier` → `GameSpeedMultiplier` here, at its two call sites in `BattleHUD.cs`, and in `Combat.md` (Core Rule 10 + an Acceptance Criterion, both named it directly).",
      "line": 40
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "THe comment is confusing, use short easy to understand comment instead.\r\n\r\nIn short, \"Place player's unit on the grid\", correct?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** Comment simplified to \"Place player's unit on the grid — wherever the player dragged it.\" The loop itself was also extracted into a shared `PlaceUnitOnGrid()` method — see the next comment.",
      "line": 67
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "In short, \"Place enemy's unit on the grid\", correct?\r\n\r\nChange the comment here too.\r\n\r\nMaybe group 67 adn 80 line function as 1 function, \"PlaceUnitOnGrid()\".\r\n\r\nIs that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED.** The two loops had identical bodies (only the source dictionary differed), so extracted into `private void PlaceUnitOnGrid(Dictionary<string, HexCoord> placements)`, called once for `_playerPlacements` and once for `GetAutoEnemyPlacements()`. Comment simplified to \"Place enemy's unit on the grid — auto-generated from the SAME source BattleBoardManager spawns enemy GameObjects from, so sprites and sim can't desync.\"",
      "line": 80
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "Working on the comment here.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**SKIPPED FOR NOW.** No concrete ask yet — revisit when there's a specific change wanted here.",
      "line": 101
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "Now, we have the main AutoBattleSim to run each hero tick, reset their attack/movement cooldown, correct?\r\nI don't like that idea, I don't sure why.\r\n\r\nBut if it was me, I would have:\r\n1 manager = AutoBattleSim\r\n1 worker = HeroSimulation => Responsibility of containing logic for that specific hero e.g. attack, movement, trait, skill, mana, etc...\r\nThen, let AutoBattleSim order each hero that's \"your turn now\". \r\n\r\nIs that make sense? Do I miss something? I think this way we have better readability.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** Your read of the current behavior is correct, and your instinct that something's off is fair — but I don't think the worker-per-hero split removes the coupling you're sensing, it relocates it. Three things stay global no matter where the code lives: (1) turn ORDER — attackers are processed fastest-`AttackSpeed`-first across ALL units, every tick, so something still has to compute that order before anyone gets a turn; (2) target-finding — `FindInRange` needs the full opponent list, not just the acting hero; (3) the win-check — fires after every single attack, checking BOTH teams. A `HeroSimulation.TakeTurn()` would still need a back-reference to the roster/grid/tuning to do any of these, so the manager doesn't shrink to a dumb dispatcher — it still computes order and still owns cross-unit queries. This also merges with the OTHER deferred question above (should HeroDataRuntime tick itself?) — your proposal is really \"invert from system-owns-data to entity-owns-behavior,\" which is a real, legitimate style (that's how traditional OOP entities work), not just readability polish. Where it actually pays off: the day two hero types need genuinely DIFFERENT turn logic (a healer, a tank taunt, a kiting archer) — right now every hero does the textually identical 4-phase dance, so there's no behavioral variance yet to justify per-hero polymorphism. My recommendation: log this merged with the ownership-inversion question as a single Open Question — \"revisit when a hero needs meaningfully different tick behavior\" — rather than do the inversion now. Want to go that route, or do you want to push ahead with prototyping the worker split anyway?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED — implemented.** New `HeroSimulation` class (`Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/HeroSimulation.cs`) wraps one `HeroDataRuntime` and owns `ChargeClocks()`/`TryAttack(opponents)`/`TryMove(opponents, grid)`/`ClampClocks()`. The manager (`AutoBattleSimulator` at the time, since renamed to `AutoChessManager`) still computes turn order, each actor's opponent list, and the win-check; `TryAttack`/`TryMove` return a small result (target id, damage / from, to) rather than firing events themselves, so `HeroSimulation` holds no reference back to the manager. `AutoBattleSimulator.Attack.cs` and `.CombatHelpers.cs` (Attack/HandleKill/MoveTowardNearest/FindInRange/ApplyDamageAndCheckKill) are deleted — their logic moved into `HeroSimulation`. `Combat.md` and `Skill.md` updated to match (Core Rule 1 reworded, the four-phase description, Interactions/Dependencies/Cross-References tables). Verified with a full battle: skill casts, mana arming, kills, and the win condition all fire correctly through the new split.",
      "line": 109
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/HeroSimulation.cs",
      "description": "Could we rename this to \"MoveTowardNearestEnemy\"\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** This comment landed mid-refactor — `AutoBattleSimulator.Attack.cs` (where `MoveTowardNearest` used to live) no longer exists; its logic is now inside `HeroSimulation.TryMove()` as part of the manager/worker split above. There's no longer a separate `MoveTowardNearest` method to rename — the nearest-opponent-finding and the step are both just steps inside `TryMove()`, which reads fine top-to-bottom on its own (it's short, and not reused elsewhere, so splitting out a named sub-method wouldn't add clarity, just a layer). Do you want the docstring on `TryMove()` to explicitly say \"moves toward the nearest enemy\" (cheap, no structural change), or do you still want a dedicated private method carved out of it for the name to attach to?",
      "line": 79
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "Could we move Combatant and Opponent to a context class that both AutoBattleSim and HeroSim have referece to? Like AutoBattleCtx.cs.\r\n\r\nNow, AutoBattleSim class to be response to resetting Combatant, and Opponent since those variable is needed by HeroSimulation.\r\nThis lead to AutoBattleSim have to send ugly parameter to HeroSimulation.\r\nAlso I don't like manager class to have a helper function like this.\r\n\r\nIf we move them out to AutoBattleCtx, HeroSim can have direct ref to it, reducing ugly parameter.\r\n\r\nIs that make sense?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**Claude's reply:** The duplication is real (the opponents-list LINQ block appeared twice, identically) — but `AutoBattleCtx` would fix it by giving `HeroSimulation` a direct reference to `_combatants`, which is the same coupling as a back-reference to the manager, just renamed. That undoes the decoupling decision from a few turns ago (you picked \"manager fires events from the result\" specifically so `HeroSimulation` stays independently testable). Recommending the duplication get fixed a different way — see the next comment's resolution.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED, twice.** First pass: extracted `GetOpponentsOf(actor)` as a private method on the manager. **Then superseded** by your follow-up request to not have helper functions on the manager class at all — see the next comment's resolution, which moved this (and the other two) into a new dedicated `AutoChessHelper` class.",
      "line": 126
    },
    {
      "file": "Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessManager.cs",
      "description": "This is also look like more of a helper funciton which I think shouldn't stay in manager class.\r\n\r\n---\r\n**RESOLVED, twice.** First pass extracted `CheckWinCondition()`/`HandleAttackResult()` as private methods on the manager (per this comment). **Then superseded**, alongside the `AutoBattleSimulator` → `AutoChessManager` rename: all three (`GetOpponentsOf`/`CheckWinCondition`/kill-handling) moved into a new dedicated `AutoChessHelper` class (`Assets/Scripts/Battle/Resolver/AutoChessHelper.cs`) — static, stateless, takes `_combatants`/`_grid` as parameters, same decoupled pattern as `HeroSimulation`. It does NOT fire events itself (`HandleKillIfNeeded()` only does grid cleanup + logging); the manager still fires `OnCombatantActed`/`OnCombatantDefeated`, since events live there. `Combat.md`'s Interactions table updated with an `AutoChessHelper` row. Verified with a full battle: identical outcome (116 ticks, Players Win).",
      "line": 132
    }
  ]
}